{
    "blocks": [
        {
            "id": "intro_looping",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Looping Through Dictionaries",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Looping through dictionaries is different from looping through lists. You can loop through keys, values, or both together."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "This is useful for processing all items in a dictionary, like printing a phone book or calculating totals."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "looping_keys",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Looping Through Keys",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "We can loop through a dictionary using a `for` loop with the `in` operator. By default, looping through a dictionary gives you the **keys**."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "student = {\n    \"name\": \"Alice\",\n    \"age\": 20,\n    \"grade\": \"A\"\n}\n\nfor key in student:\n    print(key)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "name\nage\ngrade"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The loop goes through each key in the dictionary."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "accessing_values_in_loop",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can use the key to access its value inside the loop."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "prices = {\n    \"apple\": 1.50,\n    \"banana\": 0.75,\n    \"orange\": 1.20\n}\n\nfor item in prices:\n    print(f\"{item}: ${prices[item]}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "apple: $1.5\nbanana: $0.75\norange: $1.2"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "We loop through keys (`item`) and use them to get values (`prices[item]`)."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
